\description{
Computes each respondent's personal reliability. Within each scale block (given by
\code{items$scale}) the items are split into two halves, each half's mean is formed, and
the two half-mean vectors are correlated across scale blocks, Spearman-Brown
corrected (\verb{2r / (1 + r)}, clamped at \code{-1}), and negated. A careful respondent's
halves correlate highly (low negated score); a careless respondent's decouple, so
high values flag carelessness.
}
\details{
The two variants differ only in how each scale is halved:
\itemize{
\item \strong{PR} (Jackson, 1976; \code{resample = FALSE}): a single deterministic split, first
half of each scale against the second.
\item \strong{RPR} (Goldammer et al., 2024; \code{resample = TRUE}, default, recommended): averages
the statistic over \code{n_resamples} random within-scale splits.
}

\strong{Reproducibility.} RPR draws random splits, so the default \code{seed = NULL} gives
different scores per call; pass an integer \code{seed} for a reproducible run (applied
locally, restoring the caller's RNG state, and assuming the same \code{\link[=RNGkind]{RNGkind()}}). PR is
deterministic and ignores \code{seed} and \code{n_resamples}.

\strong{Reverse-keying.} Reverse-keyed items (\code{items$reverse_keyed}) are reverse-scored
with \code{(min + max) - x} before the half-means, so the index sees trait-aligned
responses. \code{min} defaults to \code{1}; declare \code{items$min} for a 0-based or bipolar scale.

\strong{Cutoff.} The default flags at the \code{1 - fpr} quantile (95th percentile), a ranking
convention that flags at least \code{fpr} of respondents rather than a calibrated
false-positive rate. Adjust with \code{fpr}, or pass an absolute \code{cutoff} in \verb{[-1, 1]};
the two are mutually exclusive.

\strong{Score range.} The Spearman-Brown clamp maps every across-block correlation at or
below \code{-1/3} to exactly \code{+1}, giving the negated per-iteration score a point mass at
\code{+1} (PR returns it directly, RPR averages it). A percentile cutoff landing on the
atom flags more than \code{fpr} of respondents.

\strong{Abstention.} A respondent with fewer than two scorable scale blocks, or whose
half-mean vectors have no across-scale variance, has no defined correlation (\code{value},
\code{flagged} are \code{NA}); for RPR, only when every iteration abstains. With exactly two
scorable blocks the correlation is \code{+1}/\code{-1} by construction -- a degenerate score
returned with a typed warning; \verb{>= 3} multi-item scales are recommended.
}
\section{What this catches}{

Random, alternating, and opposite-pattern responding whose within-scale halves
diverge. It misses pure straightlining and midpoint locking (the constant row
abstains) -- catch those with \code{\link[=cier_longstring]{cier_longstring()}} and \code{\link[=cier_irv]{cier_irv()}}.
}

